data.content:
Three breaking changes affect your code. Here's each one with the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — no longer accepts expression trees

The setter parameter changed from `Expression<Func<...>>` to `Func<...>`. Your manual expression tree code **won't compile**. Replace it with a simple lambda:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

This is the whole point of the change — dynamic construction no longer needs expression trees.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two changes

**a) Duplicate names are now uniquified.** If `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously shared a `Street` column, EF 10 appends a number (e.g. `Street1`). To preserve the old shared-column behavior (if intentional), pin names explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});
```

**b) Nested complex types now use the full path.** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` previously mapped to column `BillingAddress_City`; it now maps to `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To keep the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

> **Important:** If you have existing migrations/databases, the column renames will produce a new migration. Pin with `HasColumnName` to avoid schema changes, or generate a migration and verify.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method (`CommandReaderExecuting`, `CommandReaderExecuted`, etc.) now requires an additional `string logCommandText` parameter. This carries the redacted SQL for logging. Update your signature:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)    // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual executed SQL
    }
}
```

Update **all** methods on the interface — `CommandScalarExecuting`, `CommandNonQueryExecuting`, and their `*Executed` counterparts all gained this same parameter.
